        <p class="lead">After building e-commerce stores on both platforms for over 40 Gujarat businesses, we have a clear sense of when each one wins. The right choice depends on your budget, your technical setup, how much control you want, and whether you plan to sell domestically or internationally.</p>

        <h2 id="fundamental-difference">The fundamental difference</h2>
        <p>Shopify is a fully hosted, subscription-based platform. You pay a monthly fee and Shopify manages the servers, security patches, and infrastructure. Everything happens inside Shopify's dashboard.</p>
        <p>WooCommerce is a free WordPress plugin that converts a WordPress website into an e-commerce store. You own your hosting, your server, and your files. More flexibility, more responsibility, typically lower long-term cost.</p>
        <p>Neither is better in isolation. A Surat textile retailer launching their first online store with a &#8377;30,000 budget has different needs than an Ahmedabad electronics business doing &#8377;50 lakh in monthly online sales. The platform that serves one well may be wrong for the other entirely.</p>

        <h2 id="true-cost">True cost comparison for indian businesses</h2>
        <p>This is where most comparisons fail. They quote Shopify's headline price without accounting for India-specific costs. Here is a complete picture:</p>
        <p><strong>Shopify annual costs (Basic plan):</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Platform fee: approximately &#8377;18,000/year (Basic plan billed annually)</li>
          <li>Transaction fee: 2% per order when not using Shopify Payments (Shopify Payments is not available in India, so this applies to every Indian store)</li>
          <li>Payment gateway fee: Razorpay charges an additional 2% per transaction</li>
          <li>Total payment cost per &#8377;100 sale: approximately &#8377;4 (Shopify's 2% + Razorpay's 2%)</li>
          <li>Essential apps: &#8377;12,000 to &#8377;36,000/year for email marketing, reviews, loyalty, etc.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>WooCommerce annual costs:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Plugin: Free</li>
          <li>Hosting: &#8377;6,000 to &#8377;18,000/year (depending on plan and traffic)</li>
          <li>Domain: &#8377;800 to &#8377;1,500/year</li>
          <li>Transaction fee: Razorpay charges 2% per transaction, no additional platform fee</li>
          <li>Total payment cost per &#8377;100 sale: approximately &#8377;2 (Razorpay only)</li>
          <li>Premium plugins: &#8377;5,000 to &#8377;15,000/year</li>
        </ul>
        <p>For a store doing &#8377;5,00,000 in monthly sales, the 2% difference in transaction fees equals &#8377;10,000/month saved on WooCommerce. That is &#8377;1,20,000/year in savings that does not appear in Shopify's pricing page. This is the most important number for high-volume Indian stores.</p>

        <h2 id="ease-of-use">Ease of use</h2>
        <p>Shopify wins here, clearly. The admin dashboard is clean and intuitive. Adding products, setting up shipping zones, running discount codes, and reading sales reports all work without any technical knowledge. A business owner in Ahmedabad can learn to manage a Shopify store in a day.</p>
        <p>WooCommerce requires WordPress comfort. Basic product management is not complicated, but troubleshooting plugin conflicts, managing hosting renewals, handling WordPress updates, and dealing with server issues requires either technical knowledge or a developer you can call. For business owners who want to manage their store independently without ongoing technical support, Shopify removes friction.</p>

        <h2 id="payment-gateways">Payment gateways: india-specific reality</h2>
        <p>WooCommerce supports Razorpay, PayU, CCAvenue, Instamojo, Cashfree, and every major Indian payment gateway as a free or low-cost plugin, with no additional platform transaction fee beyond the gateway's own charges.</p>
        <p>Shopify supports Razorpay and a handful of other Indian gateways through third-party apps, but charges its own transaction fee on top of the gateway fee on all plans except Shopify Plus. There is no way to avoid this double fee structure for Indian Shopify stores.</p>
        <p>For businesses doing high transaction volumes, this is often the deciding factor. A manufacturer in Rajkot selling to B2B buyers online, processing 200 orders/month at an average &#8377;8,000 per order, saves &#8377;32,000/month on WooCommerce versus Shopify Basic on transaction fees alone.</p>

        <h2 id="seo">SEO capabilities</h2>
        <p>WooCommerce (built on WordPress) offers deeper SEO control. With Yoast SEO or Rank Math, you can manage title tags, meta descriptions, schema markup, XML sitemaps, breadcrumbs, and canonical URLs with precision. URL structures are fully customisable.</p>
        <p>Shopify has improved significantly but still has limitations. All product URLs must include /products/ and all collection URLs must include /collections/. These cannot be changed. Duplicate content can be an issue (Shopify creates multiple URL paths for the same product when accessed through different collections). These issues are manageable but require deliberate attention.</p>
        <p>For businesses where organic search is a primary acquisition channel, WooCommerce's flexibility gives a meaningful long-term advantage.</p>

        <!-- Mid-article CTA -->
        <div class="mid-cta">
          <div class="mid-cta-inner">
            <span class="mid-cta-tag">Free Consultation</span>
            <h3>Not sure which platform fits your Gujarat business?</h3>
            <p>We have built e-commerce stores on both Shopify and WooCommerce for businesses across Ahmedabad, Surat, Vadodara, and Gandhinagar. We can assess your specific needs and recommend the right platform before you commit.</p>
